  "computational_details": [],
  "unmapped_findings": [
    "Kinetics: Log-log plots of weight gain versus time (Fig. 1) show breakaway and healing behavior for non-protective alloys and near-parabolic behavior for protective alumina formers. The rate equation (ΔW/A)^n = kt yielded a large range of n values, indicating few alloys obeyed simple rate equations; ΔW/24 values were used for comparison of oxidation rates.",
    "Table I (24 hr at 800°C): Weight gains of Fe-Mn-Al alloys span from approximately 0.021 mg cm^-2 (Fe-9Mn-4Al) to over 1 mg cm^-2 (Fe-20Mn-6Al, 18 hr). Minimum weight gains occur in the composition range Fe-(5–10)%Mn-(6–10)%Al (e.g., Fe-5Mn-7Al: 0.033; Fe-10Mn-6Al: 0.054; Fe-5Mn-9Al: 0.021 mg cm^-2). Additions of less than 2% Mn greatly increased oxidation rate of binary Fe-Al alloys, whereas 5–10% Mn significantly reduced it.",
    "Table II (100 hr): Fe-10Mn-6Al weight gains: 0.171 (600°C), 0.117 (800°C), 0.450 (1000°C) mg cm^-2. Fe-20Mn-8Al: 0.101 (600°C), 0.242 (800°C, unreliable due to spalling), 0.253 (1000°C, unreliable due to spalling) mg cm^-2.",
    "Table III (Fe-Mn-Al-Cr at 800°C): Fe-10Mn-4Al-12Cr showed lowest 24h weight gain 0.061 mg cm^-2 among Cr alloys; Fe-5Mn-5Al-5Cr: 0.068; Fe-7.5Mn-5Al-5Cr: 0.063. Fe-15Mn-5Al-5Cr showed highest 24h gain 2.663 mg cm^-2. Fe-5Mn-4Al-5Cr data 0.292 mg cm^-2 corresponds to 15 hr oxidation.",
    "Oxide map (Fig. 3) at 800°C classifies alloys into four regions superimposed on the phase diagram: Region I (insufficient Al, alumina + bulky nodules), Region II (duplex α+γ, alumina + bulky Mn-rich oxides + threads), Region III (fully ferritic, continuous protective alumina, Fe-(5–10)%Mn-(6–10)%Al), Region IV (>9% Al, alumina + small penetrating Mn oxide nodules).",
    "Fig. 17 schematic of nodule structures at 800°C: Type 1 (large iron oxide nodules, <5% Mn) has Fe2O3 outer, (Fe,Mn)3O4 inner, discontinuous Al2O3/aluminate. Type 2 (5–7.5% Mn) similar with partial healing layer. Type 3 (≥7.5% Mn) small Mn-rich nodules with continuous Mn2O3 outer layer and complete healing layer of Al2O3/aluminate at base; absence of (Fe,Mn)3O4 due to continuous aluminate.",
    "Fig. 18 schematic of duplex alloy oxidation stages: (1) alumina forms over ferrite matrix, (2) austenite nucleates and grows beneath alumina, (3) Mn2O3 threads grow at weaknesses in alumina, (4) threads incorporated into bulky Mn-rich oxide with Mn depletion and austenite conversion back to ferrite, (5) continuous healing layer of Al2O3 or (Fe,Mn)Al2O4 forms.",
    "Fig. 20 schematic of Region IV small nodule growth mechanism: (1) void formation beneath alumina scale, (2) flaw formation in overlying alumina, (3) outward growth of Mn2O3, (4) filling of void via short-circuit oxygen diffusion, (5) formation of Al2O3 or (Fe,Mn)Al2O4 particles at oxide-metal interface, (6) healing layer formation and conversion of nodule to Mn2O3.",
    "Key conclusions: The most oxidation resistant alloys have compositions within the range Fe-(5–10)%Mn-(6–10)%Al, are totally ferritic, and develop continuous protective alumina scales. Austenite is detrimental as it promotes breakdown of preexisting alumina scales and growth of bulky manganese rich oxides. Small additions of chromium are beneficial and reduce the concentration of aluminum required to form protective alumina scales."
  ]
